ramatic declines in gender inequality, evidenced by the rise of egalitarian views on gender roles and the narrowing of long-standing gender gaps in university attendance and labor force participation. This development, while spectacular, has been coupled with similarly impressive forms of resistance to equalization, most notably the continuing tendency for women to crowd into female “occupational ghettos.” This book answers the important questions: Why has such extreme segregation persisted even as other types of gender inequality have lessened? Why is segregation especially extreme in precisely those countries that appear most committed to egalitarian reform and family-friendly policies?  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Gender Studies.2bisacsh1 aChang, Mariko, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCharles, Maria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrusky, David B., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aGrusky, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHan, Joon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSørensen, Jesper B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWeeden, Kim A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertStanford University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831107042040 cprintz978080473634340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150361818340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503618183423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503618183/original  a978-3-11-070420-4  Stanford University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles